<TEXT>
legislation to double the life span of a 
fiveyear program to curb steel imports was introduced in the senate 
on wednesday as critics claimed the quotas hurt the us economy and 
no longer are needed to protect domestic steelmakers 
the bill introduced by sens john d rockefeller dwva and 
john heinz rpa would extend the socalled voluntary restraint 
agreements for another five years beyond their scheduled september 
expiration 
the restraint pacts which currently cover 19 countries and the 
european community first were negotiated in 1984 to protect the 
beleaguered us industry from foreign producers who were dumping 
cheaper subsidized steel 
domestic steelmakers since then have scaled down and modernized 
their operations and rebounded they earned more than 2 billion in 
profits in 1988 operated at 96 percent of capacity and increased 
productivity 
rockefeller said the fruits of the restraint agreements are 
just beginning to be seen and that more time and investment is 
needed before domestic steelmakers can compete without the import 
limits 
this is not protection for the industry rockefeller said 
it is simply giving us a chance to survive and rebuild 
however a coalition of more than 190 steelusing companies and 
organizations announced it had organized to fight any extension of 
the quotas saying that continuing the restraints would do more harm 
than good 
the coalition of american steel using manufacturers released a 
study by the stern group an international trade advisory group 
which concluded that the quotas may help steelmakers in the short 
term but they burden steelusing industries cost jobs reduce 
exports and slow economic growth 
we and our workers are paying a terrible price to protect the 
us steel industry said timothy l elder of caterpillar inc in 
peoria ill a member of the coalition were paying through 
higher prices than our foreign competitors are paying for their 
steel were paying through availability problems that hamstring our 
operations on the factory floor 
paula stern a former chairwoman of the us international trade 
commission and president of the stern group said the groups study 
found that steel prices in the united states have risen 15 percent 
overall since 1986 and up to 40 percent for some steel products 
she said that because voluntary restraint agreements lead to 
higher steel prices and steel shortages extending them will hurt 
americas manufacturing industries stifle its export economy and 
worsen the us trade deficit 
heinz maintained that charges the restraints have caused higher 
prices and shortages are utterly without foundation 
the senators released a report by the congressional research 
service which found that foreign steelmakers did not fill their 
quotas during the first half of last year and any domestic 
increases in steel prices experienced after early in 1988 might not 
be explained by the vra quotas 
president bush during the fall campaign said he would support 
an extention of the import limits and heinz said the presidents 
staff has reaffirmed his commitment to renew the program the 
legislation was introduced with support from 46 cosponsors 
