<TEXT>
the nations highest court on 
wednesday affirmed the convictions of two elderly doctors for taking 
part in the nazis mercy killing of more than 11500 handicapped 
people 
the ruling ended one of the last major nazirelated trials in 
west germany and closed out 28 years of criminal proceedings against 
dr aquilin ulrich and dr heinrich bunke 
in may 1987 a frankfurt court convicted ulrich and bunke of 
accessory to murder for participating in the killing of thousands of 
people most of them mentally retarded during 1940 and 1941 
ulrich and bunke both now 74 years old claimed they were 
following orders as part of the nazis euthanasia action which 
also was aimed at some physically handicapped people 
the federal court of justice in karlsruhe ruled there was proof 
bunke took part in the gaschamber deaths of at least 9200 patients 
and that ulrich killed at least 2340 people 
while affirming the convictions of accessory to murder the court 
also ordered the original sentence of four years reduced to three 
years for each doctor 
both doctors are now free as they were throughout their 
trial frankfurt prosecutors spokesman gernot broschat told the 
associated press i assume that they will go to prison 
both men say they are in failing health and are likely to resist 
any efforts to imprison them 
the two served as deputy directors at the brandenburg camp near 
berlin and in the bernburg camp near the northwestern part of what 
is now east germany 
evidence at the trial showed the doctors role included examining 
incoming patients and fabricating causes of death to report to 
victims relatives others at the camps were primarily responsible 
for the actual operation of the gas chambers 
the nazis claimed their euthanasia action was designed to help 
hopelessly ill patients with no hope of recovery more than 70000 
such patients were killed 
ulrike and bunke who both practiced gynecology after world war 
ii went on trial in the 1960s following lengthy investigations 
they were acquitted when the court ruled they were forced by the 
nazis to take part in the mercy killings 
the federal court of justice overturned the ruling in 1970 and 
ordered a retrial which was delayed for years by the ill health of 
both doctors 
ulrich practiced in the southern city of stuttgart after world 
war ii and bunke worked in the northeastern town of celle 
