<TEXT>
the cost of telephone service rose 13 percent 
in 1988 far less than the 44 percent overall increase in 
inflation the federal communications commission said wednesday 
the fcc said residential phone service cost an average 1233 in 
october 1988 for unlimited calling excluding longdistance rates 
the same service cost an average 1244 in october 1987 and 1258 
in october 1986 the fcc said 
when subscriber line charges and taxes are included the average 
rate for unlimited calling in october was 1659 
the fcc said bureau of labor statistics figures show that the 
real cost of telephone service including longdistance dropped 
about 3 percent in 1988 when inflation is taken into consideration 
in 1987 the cost of telephone service also dropped 13 percent 
compared with a 44 percent increase in inflation for a real 
decline of nearly 6 percent 
the figures were reported in the fccs telephone rates update a 
twiceyearly survey of phone costs in 95 cities 
the survey found that local service rates increased 45 percent 
on average while state toll rates decreased 42 percent interstate 
longdistance rates also dropped 42 percent on average 
the agency said that for the first time its survey included local 
business telephone service 
it found that single line business customers paid an average of 
4006 per month for local touch tone service including subscriber 
line charges and taxes and 200 short calls in cities where 
unlimited calling was not offered 
the fcc said lowerpriced options for phone service such as 
lifeline and link up were provided in 92 of the 95 cities surveyed 
the average monthly price for the lowest priced generally available 
service was 920 including subscriber line charges and taxes 
subscriber line charges currently 260 a month for residential 
customers are the fees local telephone companies charge to connect 
customers with longdistance networks 
</TEXT>
