<TEXT>
a strike at the nations largest power 
plant picked up strength wednesday drawing a sharp government 
rebuke that it could mar the atmosphere at continuing talks with the 
banned solidarity trade union 
the coal mine at the belchatow power complex 90 miles southwest 
of warsaw was shut down wednesday with the widening of a partial 
work stoppage that started monday state television and solidarity 
reported 
the shutdown came the same day that a working group of about 40 
solidarity and government representatives met in warsaw on reaching 
a consensus on the nations economic problems the meeting was part 
of broader talks that began monday 
the power plant produces 20 percent of polands energy according 
to a strike committee spokesman and was burning its threeday 
reserve of coal 
state tv said 4000 workers were on strike while the solidarity 
information service in warsaw put the number at 8000 the complex 
employs 12500 workers 
the dispute involves implementation of previously negotiated pay 
raises said edward olszewski of the strike committee he said one 
management offer was rejected wednesday and the situation is very 
tense because of the threat to power supplies for central poland 
the workers led by local solidarity activists seek a monthly 
pay increase of about 59 the official average wage is about 145 a 
month but the strike committee spokesman said the rate is skewed by 
the higher salaries of managers and few workers receive that much 
the publicly owned complex is part of a coalandpower monopoly 
formed last year in a government restructuring that removed some 
industry from direct state control the government has warned 
against enterprises paying wages that exceed their financial 
earnings with raises pegged to higher productivity 
solidarity leader lech walesa sent an envoy to see the strikers 
but government spokesman jerzy urban accused the envoy coal miner 
alojzy pietrzyk of endorsing and encouraging the strike at a rally 
attended by thousands of workers rather than trying to ease it 
i must express decisive anxiety for the sense of the round 
table talks and chances for agreement agreement is not posible 
under strike pressure urban said 
the present partners at the round table linking themselves to 
solidarity traditions sat at the table for seeking agreement 
rejecting confrontation methods how then should one assess that a 
participant referring to lech walesa warms up the workers to 
strike urban told state media 
signs of labor tension appeared elsewhere workers at the coke 
department of the strikeprone nowa huta steel mill near krakow have 
been refusing since feb 1 to work overtime solidarity spokesmen 
reported 
at another power plant the dolna odra near szczecin members of 
the official trade union told officials they are protesting their 
pay but no strike was declared according to the staterun pap news 
service 
solidarity spokesman wojciech maziarski said he had no 
information about the dolna ordra situation and that the union was 
seeking information from pietrzyk in order to reply to urbans 
accusations 
the strike has put both sides in the talks in a delicate 
position since communist party officials entered the negotiations 
despite internal opposition from hardliners arguing that an 
agreement with solidarity would help keep labor peace 
earlier wednesday the government and opposition representatives 
held the first meeting of a working group on the economy 
participants looked at economic and social issues seeking a 
consensus to reverse the stagnation inflation and shortages that 
have sapped polands progress they agreed to meet again monday 
the debates today were considered by our side as interesting 
and promising said government spokesman zbyslaw rakowski among 
the issues raised were priceandincomes policy rationing of meat 
the crushing foreign debt and spending on the military he said 
a government plan on consolidating the economy was proposed by 
authorities as a starting point for the talks but officials said 
they remain open to proposals rykowski said 
opposition spokesmen said they emphasized the need for the public 
to have a voice in curbing unwise economic decisions by authorities 
we think that all basic decisions in the system of managing the 
economy and in economic policy should be under societys control 
said witold trzeciakowski an economist who led the opposition 
delegation 
two other working groups on trade unions and political freedoms 
will meet this week all part of the historic talks that have 
brought together leaders from the communist party the opposition 
and the roman catholic church 
a chief goal of the negotiations expected to last up to six 
weeks is the legalization of solidarity the east blocs first 
independent trade union outlawed in 1982 after a martiallaw 
crackdown other reforms also are on the table including opposition 
participation in the communistcontrolled parliament 
neither walesa nor interior minister czeslaw kiszczak were at the 
talks wednesday wladyslaw baka the ruling politburo member 
responsible for the economy and witold trzeciakowski an economist 
on a citizens committee formed by walesa were the senior 
participants 
