<TEXT>
a harvard university organic chemist who 
was awarded the lucrative japan prize for 1989 on wednesday received 
his doctorate at the age of 22 and was a full professor of chemistry 
by the age of 27 
elias j corey a leader in the development of bioorganic 
substances used for therapy was chosen for the 387600 award for 
his work in synthesizing prostaglandins key regulatory substances 
in the body 
corey 71 was one of two american scientists who won the 1989 
prizes the other was a university of californiairvine professor 
f sherwood rowland 61 who has led the campaign to protect the 
earths ozone layer 
the awards considered japans version of the nobel prize were 
announced in tokyo wednesday by the prize foundation and will be 
presented april 12 they are given for scientific achievements 
contributing to world peace and prosperity 
this prize is an unequaled honor for several reasons not the 
least of which is the extraordinary quality of scientific research 
in japan in fields such as my own corey said in a statement 
released through harvard i am appreciative and delighted both to 
receive the japan prize and to be so connected with the country 
corey was the winner in this years medical science category 
rowland was the first scientist to point out the mechanisms by 
which chlorofluorocarbons could destroy the ozone layer which 
protects life on earth from harmful ultraviolet solar radiation 
prize officials said he won for environmental science and 
technology 
i am deeply honored to be selected to receive the 1989 japan 
prize and know that the honor really extends to the many colleagues 
including several from japan representing 20 countries who have 
worked with me on problems in global atmospheric chemistry 
rowland said in a statement 
much of rowlands work has been done in cooperation with mario 
molina at the national aeronautics and space administrations jet 
propulsion laboratory in pasadena calif 
corey was the first researcher to synthesize pure prostaglandins 
in a natural optically active form allowing largescale production 
of natural prostaglandins to provide a stable supply for other 
researchers officials said 
prostaglandins are hormones or hormonelike substances that may be 
involved in control of blood pressure and other important body 
processes corey won in the field of medical science 
kisaburo yokota chairman of the prize foundation told a news 
conference the recipients were selected from 407 candidates 
recommended from 44 countries the 26member selection committee is 
headed by takashi mukaido acting chairman of the atomic energy 
commission of japan 
the foundation a nonprofit organization established under the 
direction of the prime ministers office selects two science and 
technology fields each year for its awards next years fields are 
the technology of integration and earth science officials said 
the foundation was set up with a fund of 25 billion yen 194 
million contributed by matsushita electric industrial co and the 
companys founder and executive adviser konosuke matsushita 
fifteen scientists including nine americans have previously won 
the 5yearold prize 
after earning his doctorate at the massachusetts institute of 
technology corey taught at the university of illinois from 1951 to 
1959 he became a full professor of chemistry in 1956 at the age of 
27 he has been sheldon emery professor of chemistry at harvard 
since 1965 
</TEXT>
