<TEXT>
the kinsey institutes board of trustees 
gave a vote of confidence to its besieged director wednesday and 
called for an outside review of the sex research conducted during 
her tenure 
the trustees said a review conducted last year by a faculty 
committee was flawed and had misled university administrators who 
called for the resignation of the institutes director june 
reinisch in december 
in a statement the trustees said the new review would be 
conducted by a panel of experts not affiliated with indiana 
university which houses and partially funds the 40yearold 
institute 
the previous review had presented no evidence to substantiate 
charges made against reinisch by anonymous accusers the board said 
those charges included that reinisch has managed the institute 
poorly and failed to conduct enough research during her six years 
there 
unfortunately these charges have been accepted by the internal 
review committee as true and they appear to have misled university 
administrators about the quality of her contribution the 
statement said 
the board said reinisch may have made errors of administrative 
judgment and offended some institute workers but while these 
faults are serious they are not worthy of public censure 
the second review will deal only with testimony on the quality of 
the research conducted during reinischs tenure 
reinisch who is president of the 10member board of trustees 
said she had nothing to do with writing the statement and did not 
vote on whether to release it 
obviously i am very relieved to have a public statement from 
my board of trustees she said 
if theres going to be an outside review i hope that it will 
be done as quickly as possible since weve been through a very long 
period of turmoil and it will be another period of uncertainty 
reinisch said 
the trustees noted that university regulations require a second 
review by outsiders but none had been commissioned 
the statement recognized reinischs many achievements 
including bringing more recognition to the institute and starting 
programs to help the public with sex information 
although the board said there might have been more research 
produced during reinischs tenure they cited a negative climate 
in federal support the timeconsuming nature of revitalizing a 
moribund organization and the distractions of accusations made 
against her 
since her arrival at kinsey reinisch has brought in more than 
34 million 
