<TEXT>
housing prices have had a startling rise in many 
sections of the country in the past decade or so leaving analysts 
still searching for the reasons why and wondering if something still 
eludes their calculations 
popular explanations have included the rising cost of land a 
surge in the number of couples in the prime homebuying years of 
ages 25 to 34 restrictive building and zoning codes a tax code 
that feeds demand and rising rents 
whatever the reason the median price of existing homes has risen 
from 48700 in 1978 to 70300 in 1983 to 85600 in 1987 and 
88100 in october of 1988 in august 1988 it was even higher at 
91400 
an even sharper ascent can be traced for new homes which sold 
for a median price of 55700 in l978 and 75300 in 1983 last year 
the median price more than doubled that of a decade earlier 
reaching 118000 at one point 
while at least a score of additional reasons can be offered for 
the ascent one factor is sometimes overlooked that is bigger 
more rooms baths square footage and probably better houses 
quality materials central airheat are being built today buyers 
are trading up not just in price but in product too 
over a relatively short period of time these improvements can be 
traced in 1972 for example the census bureau found that only 43 
percent of new singlefamily houses had central air conditioning in 
1987 the figure was 71 per cent 
in the same period the percentage of houses with two or more 
baths rose to 83 from 53 and those with fireplaces jumped from 38 
percent to 62 percent the percentage of houses of 1600 square feet 
or more rose to 59 from 38 
but it is over an even longer period that the improvement in 
housing becomes impressively clear 
in 1940 when the census bureau conducted its first housing 
census the median value of owneroccupied homes was 2938 the 
dollar was worth more then of course but even if you quadruple the 
price to 12000 it was low 
now consider some of the reasons in that year more than a 
million precivil war housing units were still occcupied thirtyone 
percent of the nations homes had no running water and 45 percent 
didnt have complete private plumbing wells cisterns rain barrels 
and outhouses were common 
that same census found that 143 million units or less than half 
of all homes had central heat of the 198 million housing units 
without central heating about 16 million relied on stoves 
fewer than half the homes in that year had mechanical 
refrigeration equipment while 93 million homes relied on ice 
about 99 million used other means of cooling such as spring 
houses or had no way to protect perishables 
other improvements include electricity builtin conveniences 
such as dishwashers insulation fireresistant materials patios 
pools family rooms and the electronic house of the future might 
make these seem oldfashioned 
whether you believe the house of today represents true value when 
compared to the old days is as much a matter of personal judgment as 
of any scientific cost estimate the comparison isnt made to 
justify todays prices 
in fact there exists a vocal if rather small percentage of the 
economic fraternity who believe too much money is going into 
housing and that the nation would be better served by investing the 
funds in manufacturing instead 
but any comparison of yesterday with today illustrates the point 
that housing for most people in the past was something closer to 
rudimentary shelter than in this day and age when lifestyle 
prevails and cost seems no obstacle 
</TEXT>
