<TEXT>
there is ample precedent for ronald reagan to 
make millions off his memoirs but the moneymaking activity of former 
presidents is still a sore subject with many americans 
it was in fact a basis for congress decision more than 30 
years ago to grant pensions and office allowances to former 
occupants of the white house 
the idea according to a senate committee report issued in 1986 
was to ensure that former presidents can live dignified retired 
lives free from the need to commercialize and demean their status 
as elder statesmen 
nevertheless before the law was passed and since past 
presidents have profited sometimes handsomely from writing 
speaking and business connections 
presidential scholars are divided on the propriety of reagan 
receiving a reported advance of 5 million for his memoirs and a 
book of speeches and signing a reported 40000aspeech contract 
with a lecture agency 
he should not make one dime for writing a book of what he did 
as president or for speaking thats what i think said political 
scientist james david barber of duke university a leading student 
of the presidency 
but daniel p franklin a political scientist and expert on the 
presidency at colgate university said i frankly dont see 
anything wrong with president reagan writing a book and getting some 
money we tend to hold our politicians to in some case unrealistic 
standards 
i think what it shows is that the expresident is still seen as 
a symbol and there is an idea that in some way the symbolic nature 
of the presidency is compromised just by virtue of his accepting 
monetary gain franklin said 
president bush was asked at his first presidential news 
conference on jan 27 about the reagan deals and whether he 
thought it was appropriate to cash in on the presidency 
i dont know whether id call it cashing in i expect every 
president has written his memoirs and received money for it the 
president said 
when asked whether it might not create a perception of 
wrongdoing he said no because i think theres been a long of 
history of that and i dont think its ever been challenged as 
inappropriate 
bush said he had read that president grant received 500000 for 
his memoirs at a time when half a million really meant something 
grant bankrupt and dying of throat cancer wrote his memoirs of 
the civil war in his last months in the hope of providing for his 
family eventually his heirs received 450000 in royalties 
although grant did not live to enjoy any of it his twovolume work 
is considered a classic war commentary 
as a matter of fact he was a much better autobiographer than 
he was a president said franklin 
when president truman left the white house in 1953 he wrote in 
his memoirs he turned down lucrative offers from industry some of 
them involving little work because i knew that they were not 
interested in hiring harry truman the person but what they wanted 
to hire was the former president of the united states i could never 
lend myself to any transaction however respectable that would 
commercialize on the prestige and the dignity of the office of the 
presidency 
truman did sell the rights to his memoirs to life magazine for 
600000 
nevertheless he was not a wealthy man and he answered his mail 
using his own pen and paper and paid for stamps out of his own 
pocket the 1986 report of the committee on governmental affairs 
said 
with trumans experience in mind congress enacted legislation in 
1958 giving former presidents for the first time pensions and an 
allowance for their office expenses reagan gets a federal pension 
of 99500 a year and an office allowance of up to 300000 
richard nixon after his resignation from office in 1974 in the 
wake of the watergate scandals received an advance of more than 2 
million for his memoirs plus 600000 and a share of the profits for 
a series of televised interviews with british talk show host david 
frost 
nixon like dwight eisenhower before him accepts no speaking 
fees 
he has been offered up to 100000 for speeches is routinely 
offered between 15000 and 20000 and we estimate we turn down 
about 675000 worth of offers a year for speeches said john h 
taylor the former presidents administrative assistant 
his position is that he at least as a former president feels 
most comfortable speaking out only on substance and only when he 
thinks his doing so will help the country said taylor there is 
no implied criticism of how others do it i am just telling you how 
president nixon does it 
thats fascinating said duke political scientist barber 
here you have the most unethical president of the 20th century who 
is being more ethical than the others 
nixons successor gerald ford and his wife received about 1 
million for their memoirs and ford was paid 1 million by nbc to 
appear in documentaries and be available for television interviews 
over a fiveyear period 
ford also accepted offers to serve on the boards of a number of 
corporations by 1987 he was serving on eight at fees of up to 
30000 a year and was a consultant to others at fees up to 
100000 his spokesman robert e barrett says ford is now cutting 
back on such activity 
both nixon and fords successor jimmy carter have shunned 
membership on corporate boards reagans spokesman mark weinberg 
said reagan has not accepted any that i know of and i dont know 
what plans there are in that regard 
barrett defends fords business activities saying the 
president doesnt create the opportunities those demands are there 
as a result of where society has gone in the last 15 to 20 years 
he is sitting there and hes going to do some of this stuff 
barrett said ford usually gets 15000 to 20000 for a speech 
but might speak for as little as 7500 in some cases such as 
speaking to a group in rancho mirage calif where he lives over 
the years the spokesman estimated the average fee per speech has 
been less than 12000 
former president carter received an undisclosed advance for his 
memoirs keeping faith after a number of new york publishers 
were invited to meet with him 
carter is also in emand as a speaker on college campuses most 
recently at memphis state university last month 
bob young director of the student activities council at memphis 
state said we made an offer of 10000 and it was turned down 
then i found out that if we would offer air transportation to and 
from georgia that that would help us out so i counteroffered with 
10000 plus a round trip on a private plane one of our vice 
presidents helped us get the plane donated and he accepted the 
offer 
