<TEXT>
patten corp a land company whose sales 
practices have stirred controversy has agreed to pay restitution to 
customers who can prove they were sold property under false 
pretenses according to proposed consent decrees filed wednesday in 
five northeast states 
the agreements which were scheduled to be released separately by 
officials in maine new hampshire vermont new york and 
massachusetts would end consumerfraud investigations into pattens 
activities in the five states and require patten to pay each state 
100000 
patten did not admit to any wrongdoing in the settlement and it 
was not immediately clear how much land or how many customers are 
involved 
maine attorney general james e tierney said maines interest was 
by far the largest of the five states 
this was no nickelanddime operation tierney said many 
scenic and recreational areas in maine were systematically acquired 
cut up for resale and marketed in highpressure campaigns that 
violated maine laws and preyed upon unsuspecting unknowing 
consumers 
patten brought the rogue morality of wall street to the woods 
of maine he said 
patten based in stamford conn said in a statement that it had 
cooperated fully and voluntarily with the state investigators 
many of the requirements in the agreements are already patten 
policy and the agreements will enable the company to further its 
policy of dealing fairly and quickly with customer complaints 
said the statement 
company president harry patten was quoted as saying while the 
company denies violating any consumer laws we believe the 
agreements serve the interests of the company its shareholders and 
customers 
the company said in reporting separately on its latest earnings 
results that it had taken a pretax deduction of 26 million to 
reserves which were set aside for anticipated expenses relating to 
the latest settlement as well as a tentative agreement in settlement 
of a previouslydisclosed dispute in pennsylvania 
the company believes that the amounts allocated to the reserves 
will cover all potential future costs relating to the two matters 
the statement said 
a complaint filed with the proposed settlement in superior court 
in augusta alleges that patten routinely lured customers many of 
them from other states by advertising property in rural maine at 
prices substantially lower than what was actually available 
the complaint also alleges patten misled prospective customers on 
numerous matters including the potential for building on the 
property and access to utilities roads and municipal services for 
example one unidentified buyer cited in the complaint was assured 
that utility service was available only to learn later that it 
would cost 23000 to bring electricity to the land 
under the pending maine consent decree which tierney said is 
virtually identical to those in the other states patten is required 
to make available a dispute resolution procedure to anyone who 
purchased land in the state or any resident who purchased land from 
patten between aug 1 1982 and may 1 1989 
people who can prove that patten misrepresented or omitted a 
material fact in selling the property will be entitled to full 
reimbursement including the purchase price interest taxes and 
closing costs 
customers who can show that they were forced to pay unreasonably 
high prices to improving the property because of similar 
misrepresentations are entitled to partial restitution under the 
agreement 
also any dispute that cannot be resolved within 45 days can be 
taken before the american arbitration assocation 
