<TEXT>
the arctic cold wave that blew through 
california this week sent shivers through the states 
multimilliondollar floral and citrus industries ruining part of 
the lemon crop and possibly boosting the price of a valentine 
bouquet 
as the weather moderated in the states major growing regions 
wednesday growers assessed the coldcaused damage by slicing open 
lemons and eyeing rows of drooping carnations 
theres going to be a shortage right now theyre carnations 
just not blooming said mark yamaguchi a growershipper in 
monterey county 
many growers and packers said lemon groves in the san joaquin 
valley in central califronia were hit hard by the cold wave with 
some early estimates that 35 percent of the existing crop may have 
been damaged 
california is the nations top producer of lemons a crop valued 
at 152 million in 1987 it will take about a week to 10 days for an 
accurate assessment of the frosts damage industry experts said 
but prices already have risen for some crops the industrys 
wholesale price for a 40pound box of medium sized oranges jumped 1 
to 750 and a box of larger oranges also jumped 1 to 1050 said 
george lombardi marketing director for sequoia farms in exeter 
flower growers in san mateo and santa cruz counties already have 
seen the effect on their crops 
the damage is done the freeze has damaged the crops out there 
and i dont expect them to recover at all said george ginilo 
agriculture commissioner of central californias san mateo county 
the countys 1987 floral crop was valued at 165 million and serves 
wholesalers on the west coast and in new england 
but while some major suppliers of california flowers predicted a 
shortage it was unclear whether it would affect the market by 
valentines day yamaguchi said 80 percent of the national carnation 
market comes from foreign growers 
the california farm bureau federation said imports and greenhouse 
flowers should provide a tight but adequate supply of flowers 
for valentines day but said prices may be slightly higher in 
some cases 
daisies irises pom poms babys breath and other flowers grown 
in open fields may be in short supply even with the imports said 
