<DOCNO> AP890208-0311 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a federal judge in a decision that 
effectively ends a sevenyear legal battle between two giant 
computer chip makers has ruled that microcodes can be protected by 
copyright 
us district judge william gray of los angeles ruled late 
tuesday in a suit between intel corp of santa clara calif and 
nec corp of japan 
gray settled a major aspect of the case in favor of intel 
upholding the companys contention that copyright protection extends 
to microcodes an intricate language embedded in computer chips 
although chip technology was already protected under copyright 
law that did not extend to hidden software such as microcodes 
the ruling is considered crucial to the success of the 16 
billion market for microprocessors protection of microcodes is 
viewed by analysts as a protection for us chipmakers against 
foreign competitors especially japanese companies 
the ruling cleared nec of the accusation that it illegally copied 
intels 8086 and 8088 model computers chips the chips are the key 
to the popular ibm personal computer and compatible systems 
im obviously pleased to win in any case especially this 
one said robert morrill an attorney representing nec this is 
going to be a significant case in computer copyright law and sets a 
nice balance between whats protectable and whats not 
intel lawyer f thomas dunlap called the ruling a broad 
landmark decision for the industry 
we now have a precedent that our large investments in new 
products such as the 386 microprocessor and future microprocessors 
can be protected under copyright law dunlap said 
gray said intels failure to ensure that a copyright mark be 
included on each chip made by several of its licensee companies 
meant it had forfeited it copyright on the 8086 and 8088 chips 
as a result of the decision these companies including nec may 
not be required to pay intel licensee fees to make the chips 
about 29 million ships were shipped by licensee without a 
copyright notice on them gray said 
the expensive legal battle began in 1982 when the two 
electronics giants that had once been partners began sparring the 
case went to court twice after the judge in the first case 
disqualified himself for owning a small amount of intel stock 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
