<TEXT>
president bush has approved the foreign 
takeover of the last major us producer of silicon wafers the 
vital material used to make the computer chips in most electronic 
products 
the approval allows huels ag of west germany to take over 
monsanto electronic materials co of palo alto 
us companies now produce almost none of the silicon wafers made 
in the world while japanese companies provide 70 percent and 
european companies 26 percent of the worlds supply 
its real depressing said dan hutcheson president of vlsi 
research a san jose semiconductor research firm its another 
glaring sign that says our country is losing its technical 
capability and with it the ability to support our economy and 
defend ourselves in the future 
monsanto electronic is a division of monsanto co and is the 
worlds sixthlargest producer of silicon wafers 
the sale was announced last november and bushs approval of it 
tuesday did not come as a surprise the white house was assured that 
huels would keep the silicon supplier in the united states 
the sale was reviewed by an interagency government panel under 
the provisions of last years trade bill which empowers the 
president to block foreign acquisitions of us companies if the 
deals are thought to compromise national security 
the production of silicon is the first step in making computer 
chips silicon is usually refined to the desired level of purity 
formed into tubes sliced into disks and polished semiconductor 
makers then buy the wafers and cut them into chips for etching 
